content.description: A fun way to use the holds on the pillar crack on the right arete. Anybody ever tried it? Sit start as for tall crack. Move up both hands into the crack side pulls just above the starting jug. Find your feet and make a big move out right into a gaston on the lowest hold of the crack. Toe hook the jug starting hold and cross into the next hold above your right hand. Move your body to the right and finish up the arete to the top.
content.location: Same start as tall crack.

content.description: Sit start the corner and take the easy ramps up the face.  If you follow the right arete up, instead of going up and left to the center of the face, you can get a bit more warmup value out of it.
content.location: Faces the trail/road, on the same boulder with "Tall Crack" and "Short Crack".

content.description: Sit start on the large flat edge in the corner under the roof.Move left to good hold and figure out how to tackle the roof above.
content.location: Walk in from the road and take a left, walk for a couple minutes until you see a wash on your left. This is on the second boulder in the wash, you will have to walk past it and turn around to see the obvious box-shaped features of this climb.

content.description: Sit start at the base of the obvious crack shooting straight up the block. Move straight up with some good, but crumbly and sharp locks. Look for good jugs on the right arete and top out.
content.location: Right of Finger Traverse.

content.description: Start sitting on the arete with a left hand crimp and right hand on the arete, work up the arete to the top.
content.location: When walking in from the road, this is on the first boulder you see. Climb the arete just left of the obvious crack line Lateralus.

content.description: A great left to right rising traverse. Sit start at the lowest point n the bolder with a knob for your left hand and with your right just next to it. Pull on and climb the rising lip to the right arete topping out around the corner on jugs.
content.location: Walk in from the road and head right, in ~150 yards you will see this obvious left to right rising traverse.

content.description: Finger crack to a shelf with a jug above.
content.location: South side of the large block just past Latereralus

content.description: Sit start as for Lateralus. Make one move up the crack and bust right using a crimp and wide pinch before an easy top out.
content.location: When approaching from the road, this is the first boulder you see. Sit start in the obvious crack - Lateralus - and bust right.

content.description: Cool problem on the left side of the Humphrey’s Hollow cave. Start low on the left edge of the cave. Work your way up the edge and top out on a mossy ledge half way up the boulder.  Use tree to get off.
content.location: Left side of the Hollow cave.

content.description: Felt hard might delete.....haha. Short little, three move, power problem on the right arete of the sip of sunshine boulder. Definitely not worth a special trip, but if you’re feeling strong and have some time to kill after work, give it a shot! The movement is great. Start with a left hand on the low block feature. I use a crimp in the back. Right hand on a crappy three finger dish thing to the right of the arete at about the same height. Right foot is low on a rail and left on anything that works out left. Pull on and core tension dead point to a sharp crimp just right of the arete. Lock off, and move left foot up, then throw out left to a good hold on the lip. Hold the swing then top out straight up.
content.location: Locate the Sip of Sunshine boulder. This is the obvious arete at the end of the traverse.

content.description: Sit start with right hand on the big pinch and left below it, pull up to the crimp out left and work up the arete.
content.location: When walking in from the road, take a right, follow until you see the obvious left to right traverse line of 'Sip of Sunshine'. This route shares the boulder and is the short arete on the back corner.

content.description: Climb the short layback crack
content.location: On the same boulder as Lateralus, but this route is on the opposite side that faces the road

content.description:
Stand start on two under clings at half height. Find a foot and climb to the top.

 While you’re up there sit start the route under the crescent crack and climb up. V0.
content.location: Right behind you when looking at claustrophobic aerobics.

content.description:
Climb the obvious crack from a sit start. THE classic warm up in the area. 

  Climb it.
content.location: When walking in from the road this is the first boulder you come to, the obvious crack facing uphill.

climbs.name: Iso Burn
climbs.fa: Henry Barber, barefoot, in 1973 at 5 AM, while his girlfriend was sleeping under a picnic table

content.description: Funky right to left traverse into Lateralus. A few moves kind of reminded me of the Sit Down Traverse at Lincoln Woods. Basically sit start on a rail on the pyramid feature, reach out left to the sloping shelf, then grab the holds for Rustique and transition into the crack of Lateralus and finish as for that problem. I found the move into Lateralus to be quite fun.
content.location: Start on the pyramid shaped feature 8' to the right of Lateralus

content.description:
A long right to left traverse with the crux at the end. 

  Sit start on an odd horizontal pinch with your right with your left just below it. Pull on making strenuous loves left to the far arete.
content.location: When walking in from the road, take a right and after about ~150 yards, this will be staring right at you.

content.description: Sit start in lowest horizontal. Make a move to a triangle pinch and rock up on a sloping heel hook. Needs cleaning since I sent it.
content.location: Walk in and go left on the faint trail. Problem is on the right on the third big boulder.

content.description: Sit start at the base of the obvious crack that shoots straight to the top of the block. Instead of chasing that crack move up and left to a good pod and a horizontal finger crack. Move left and finish on Short Crack.
content.location: Right of short crack.

content.description: I have no clue if this has been done before, but I cleaned it off and did it the other day. It's a bit dabby, and the crux for me was not hitting anything. That said, the movement is really, really cool and I was pleasantly surprised by how good it is. Full disclosure, my shoulder scraped a pad on the last few moves, but this in no way made it easier, so I counted it. It's just one of those problems. Plus, who even knows if someone did this before me and I want people to go try it, so I'm listing it. It starts all the way to the right of Cloud Drop, climbs through a mini roof, and then transitions to the starting feet of Cloud Drop. It adds a solid 8 or more moves to the original problem, and utilizes the entire face. As far as the grade goes, it could be harder than 6-7. I'll have to go back and reevaluate the grade. Having a large wingspan (me) certainly will help. Would love for people to go try it out and let me know!

This crack has definitely been done before from the stand. Starting with hands in the jug at mid height. I did a pretty good sit start that makes it a fun boulder problem. It should be noted that I filled in the ankle breaking trench in front of the boulder to make the landing safer (with a pad). It probably made the initial pull easier, but I’m not looking to be injured. Sit start with left hand on a side pull at the bottom of the crack. Right hand in a small three finger pod in the low horizontal crack. Choose some feet, pull on, and move into a good jam in the crack. Move up and get hands into the horizontal crack at mid height. Get a high foot and dead point into the good hold in the horizontal crack at three quarters height. Top out on good holds at the lip.
content.protection: Two pads. One to fill in the leaf filled trench.
content.location: Walk into the woods from the parking lot. Turn right and follow the trail past the Claustrophobic Aerobics boulder. On the other side of the hill you’ll see a cluster of three boulders. This is the obvious crack that faces the road.

content.description: Climb the pretty rails and overhanging face. Start sitting compressing the two verticle rails with the right hand on a good incut hold and left on the rail. Pull on, and work your way up to establish on the triangle shaped hold. From there pull up to the crimps in the upper face before moving to the jugs at the lip and pressing out the topout.
content.protection: A couple pads, the landing is a bit uneven but is easily made safe.
content.location: When you walk into Humpreys walk left, pass Vale of Shadows (which is on your left).  A few feet past, this is located in a small alcove on your right, just before the trail swings uphill.

content.description:
Great problem! Start low in the small cave. Left on a terrible pinch, right on a three finger edge. Utilizing a great toe jam and roof trickery, climb out of the cave to the nose of the boulder. Pull the roof on edges.

 Variation: Pretty much it’s own problem. Start on same holds. Climb out to the left on great holds and pull the roof with some difficulty. V5
content.protection: Two pads are nice because of the horizontal length. You‘re never more than 4 ft off the ground.
content.location: Walk up the trail to the boulder field. Follow a faint trail to the right until you get to the boulder right off the trail.

content.description: Sit start the left arete with a ramp for easy feet.  Move up the arete, place a heel, and shoot up to a nice dish next to the peak of the boulder.  Rock over the arete and top out.
content.location: Near the "Beginner's Crack" more toward the road and toward the boulder with "Goodnight Irene" on it.

content.description:
Sit down, press a foot up into a nice left-facing corner, put your hands up on the arete above. Move up the short arete until your hands reach the high point. I guess it's not V-easy if you top out (which I hope to do, one day).

 This is a fun problem for someone who rarely boulders outdoors. Short enough to allay any fears, easy enough to complete, hard enough to pose a little challenge.
content.protection: Pad. But this boulder is so short, you may not even need that.
content.location: Walk up the short trail from the road, and see a huge, friendly boulder in front of you. Turn right and start walking, counting your steps. After about 100 steps you come to the "Sip of Sunshine" boulder. To the right of that boulder is a small boulder, about 5 feet tall. This is your boulder. Throw your pad down under it and get going.

content.description: Climb up through the undercling.
content.location: Left of GNI

content.description: A bit of a one move wonder off the ground, but the crack and rock are so good it's worth a burn even if you wish the rock was perched just a bit steeper than it is. Good fun and worth a burn during a Humphrey's circuit.
content.protection: Couple Pad, watch out for the hole, but you won't blow it.
content.location: Just past the unnamed block with multiple crack lines, uphill to the right.

content.description: Start on big Jug as for Vales but head up and right through big moves and good holds to a tricky mantel.
content.location: Right hand exit to Vale of Shadows

content.description: My favorite boulder problem in the area. Start on two holds in cave. Find feet and move to a crystal edge. Make a big move to a jug on the lip and control the swing. Match hands and move right to a couple bad  bumps in a seam then bump to a incut edge and match. Reach to an undercling and stand up into it. Rest. Then move up the corner on tips lie-back to slab above.
content.protection: A few pads and a spotter. A fall in the corner could be bad.
content.location: Walk up from parking until you reach the trail going through the boulder field. Head left past the GNI boulder for 20’. Walk in to the right.

content.description:
Perhaps the shortest bouldering approach in North Conway? 

  A plethora of high-quality granite blocks strewn below the cliff at Humphrey's. Ranging from V0 - Vhard, there are plenty of quality lines to occupy climbers of all abilities.
